com.cyc.query

Class QueryResultSetImpl

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.cyc.query.QueryResultSetImpl
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    com.cyc.query.QueryResultSet, Iterable<com.cyc.query.QueryAnswer>

    public class QueryResultSetImpl
extends Object
implements com.cyc.query.QueryResultSet, Iterable<com.cyc.query.QueryAnswer>

    QueryResultSetImpl provides a class for easy access and manipulation of inference results. It tries to closely mimic the ResultSet interface, but does not implement all of its methods.

    In this paradigm, the results of a Query are a table with one row for each answer, and one column for each query variable. There is a cursor that can be moved from row to row, and various getter methods that retrieve the binding for a particular variable (i.e. the value in the column corresponding to that variable) on the current row.

    The cursor starts out just before the first row, and can be advanced to just after the last row. Otherwise, it is on whatever the current row is.

    In general, KBInferenceResult sets should not be created by application developers, but should be retrieved from a Query object using Query.getResultSet().

      • close

        public void close()
        Releases this QueryResultSetImpl object's server side inference resources. Failure to close a result set may leave significant resources hanging around the server until the client CycAccess object is closed.

        Calling the method close on a InferenceResultSet object that is already closed is a no-op.

        Specified by:
        close in interface com.cyc.query.QueryResultSet

      • next

        public boolean next()
        Moves the cursor forward one row from its current position. A QueryResultSetImpl cursor is initially positioned before the first row; the first call to the method next makes the first row the current row; the second call makes the second row the current row, and so on.
        Specified by:

      • getDate

        public Date getDate(String columnLabel)
        Returns, as a java.sql.Date object, the value in the current row at the column identified by columnLabel, which should be the name of a Variable in the original query. Returns null if no value is set for the current row and given column. This method fails on dates that do not use #$YearFn (i.e. it will not work on skolemized dates, or other forms of dates that don't use the #$YearFn vocabulary).
        Specified by:
        getDate in interface com.cyc.query.QueryResultSet

        ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException - if the current cursor is not on a valid row
        ClassCastException - if the value is not convertible to a Date

        ClassCastException - if the value is not convertible to a Date
